**Miss** (pronounced [/ˈmɪs/](/wiki/Help:IPA/English "Help:IPA/English")) is
an English language [honorific](/wiki/English_honorific "English honorific")
traditionally used only for an unmarried woman (not using another title such
as "[Doctor](/wiki/Doctor_\(title\) "Doctor \(title\)")" or
"[Dame](/wiki/Dame_\(title\) "Dame \(title\)")"). Originating in the 17th
century, it is a contraction of _[mistress](/wiki/Mistress_\(form_of_address\)
"Mistress \(form of address\)")_ , which was used for all women. A period is
not used to signify the contraction. Its counterparts are [Mrs.](/wiki/Mrs.
"Mrs."), usually used only for married women, and [Ms.](/wiki/Ms. "Ms."),
which can be used for married or unmarried women.

The plural _**Misses**_ may be used, such as in _The Misses Doe_. The
traditional French "**Mesdemoiselles** " (abbreviation "**Mlles** ") may also
be used as the plural in English language conversation or correspondence. In
Australian schools the term miss is used interchangeably with female teacher.

## Contents

  * 1 Use as a title (honorific) in the United States
  * 2 Use alone as a form of address
  * 3 Other uses
  * 4 See also
  * 5 References

## Use as a title (honorific) in the United
States[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Miss&action=edit&section=1 "Edit section: Use
as a title \(honorific\) in the United States")]

The usage of "Miss" as a title in the United States is most frequently seen
when referring to young women, or women whose marital status is unknown.
Though _Miss_ is less commonly used as a title by unmarried adult
[women](/wiki/Women "Women") in the United States than in the past, some still
prefer to be referred to as such. Twenty-first century
[etiquette](/wiki/Etiquette "Etiquette") honors an adult woman's personal
preference of title. However, if the preference is not known, "Ms." is used.
"Ms." is the preferred choice as the female title in business. It is the
equivalent to the male title "Mr." as neither is marital status specific.

_Miss_ was formerly the default title for businesswomen, but has largely been
replaced by [Ms.](/wiki/Ms. "Ms.") in this context. It was a default title for
actresses _(Miss[Helen Hayes](/wiki/Helen_Hayes "Helen Hayes"), Miss [Barbara
Stanwyck](/wiki/Barbara_Stanwyck "Barbara Stanwyck"))_ or other celebrities
_(Miss[Amelia Earhart](/wiki/Amelia_Earhart "Amelia Earhart"))_. Such default
usage has also proved problematic; the poet [Dorothy
Parker](/wiki/Dorothy_Parker "Dorothy Parker") was often referred to as _Miss
Parker_ , even though _Parker_ was the name of her first husband and she
herself preferred _Mrs. Parker_. Later in the century, the use of "Miss" or
"Mrs." became a problem for _The New York Times_ in referring to political
candidate [Geraldine Ferraro](/wiki/Geraldine_Ferraro "Geraldine
Ferraro")[_[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed
"Wikipedia:Citation needed")_], a married woman who did not use her husband's
surname, since _Mrs._ has been used with a woman's maiden name only in limited
circumstances in public life before the 1980s. (See more at [Ms.](/wiki/Ms.
"Ms."))

"Miss" is the proper form for addressing all young ladies. It is sometimes
used when addressing a younger adult woman, for example, "May I help you,
Miss?" In the [United States](/wiki/United_States "United States"), the titles
of "Ma'am" or "Madam" are sometimes used instead of "Miss." Use of any of
these terms implies marital
status.[_[dubious](/wiki/Wikipedia:Accuracy_dispute#Disputed_statement
"Wikipedia:Accuracy dispute") – [discuss](/wiki/Talk:Miss#Dubious
"Talk:Miss")_] Some take offense to the use of "Ma'am" or "Madam" because it
indicates that the speaker thinks the woman being addressed must certainly be
married due to her apparent age, and some take offense to the use of the terms
"Ma'am" or "Madam" because of their association with houses of ill repute. On
the other hand, addressing a woman as "Miss" may be taken as patronizing.

In some American subcultures, such as the [American
South](/wiki/American_South "American South") and some urban cultures, _Miss_
is sometimes used irrespective of marital status with a woman's first name in
direct or indirect informal address, as _Miss Ellen_ from _[Gone with the
Wind](/wiki/Gone_with_the_Wind_\(novel\) "Gone with the Wind \(novel\)")_ or
[_Miss Ellie_](/wiki/Miss_Ellie_Ewing "Miss Ellie Ewing") from
_[Dallas](/wiki/Dallas_\(1978_TV_series\) "Dallas \(1978 TV series\)")_. This
form was also used in [upper class](/wiki/Upper_class "Upper class")
households in some English-speaking countries by [servants](/wiki/Servant
"Servant") to address or refer to the unmarried ladies of the household, and
occasionally in family-run businesses in the same manner, though more commonly
it was used to address servants if they were addressed by title at all. This
is also common with female child-care givers; small children will refer to
their preschool teacher or nanny as "Miss" and their first name, regardless of
marital status. In some school districts in the United States, this custom
extends through the early primary school grades.

In some styles of [etiquette](/wiki/Etiquette
"Etiquette")[_[which?](/wiki/Wikipedia:Avoid_weasel_words "Wikipedia:Avoid
weasel words")_], the eldest daughter of a family was addressed on paper
simply as _Miss[Doe](/wiki/John_Doe "John Doe")_, with the younger daughters
being addressed as _Miss Jane Doe_ and _Miss Rebecca Doe_. In person, as in
when making introductions, the styling would have been extended to unmarried
cousins with the same surname.

Another notable use of _Miss_ is as the title of a [beauty
queen](/wiki/Beauty_queen "Beauty queen") (given that in most pageants it is a
requirement that contestants be unmarried), such as _[Miss
America](/wiki/Miss_America "Miss America")_ , _[Miss World](/wiki/Miss_World
"Miss World")_ , and _[Miss Universe](/wiki/Miss_Universe "Miss Universe")_.
Other languages, such as [French](/wiki/French_language "French language"),
[Spanish](/wiki/Spanish_language "Spanish language"),
[German](/wiki/German_language "German language"), and
[Portuguese](/wiki/Portuguese_language "Portuguese language"), have borrowed
the English _Miss_ to refer to the winner of a beauty pageant.

In some Mexican schools (particularly, but not exclusively, in bilingual
schools), the term _Miss_ and _female teacher_ are used interchangeably;
students often address their female teachers simply as _Miss_.
